{"action": "edit", "code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    for i in range(input_grid.shape[0]):\n        for j in range(input_grid.shape[1]):\n            if has_red_neighbors_in_horizontal_directions(input_grid, i, j):\n                input_grid = color_to_maroon(input_grid, i, j)\n    return input_grid\ndef has_red_neighbors_in_horizontal_directions(grid: np.ndarray, i: int, j: int) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"\n    Checks if there are red points in the left and right directions of the given point.\n\n    Args:\n    - grid (np.ndarray): The input grid.\n    - i (int): The row index of the point.\n    - j (int): The column index of the point.\n\n    Returns:\n    - bool: True if there are red points in the left and right directions of the given point, False otherwise.\n    \"\"\"\n    left = False\n    right = False\n    for k in range(j):\n        if grid[i][k] == red:\n            left = True\n            break\n    for k in range(j + 1, grid.shape[1]):\n        if grid[i][k] == red:\n            right = True\n            break\n    return left and right\ndef color_to_maroon(grid: np.ndarray, i: int, j: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Colors the given point in the grid to maroon.\n\n    Args:\n    - grid (np.ndarray): The input grid.\n    - i (int): The row index of the point.\n    - j (int): The column index of the point.\n\n    Returns:\n    - np.ndarray: The updated grid with the given point colored to maroon.\n    \"\"\"\n    grid[i][j] = maroon\n    return grid", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n\tfor i in range(input_grid.shape[0]):\n\t\tfor j in range(input_grid.shape[1]):\n\t\t\tif `there are red point both in left and right direction and this point is black`(input_grid, i,j):\n\t\t\t\tinput_grid = `color this point to maroon`(input_grid, i,j)\n\treturn input_grid\n\t\n\t", "gpt_code": "def has_red_neighbors_in_horizontal_directions(grid: np.ndarray, i: int, j: int) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"\n    Checks if there are red points in the left and right directions of the given point.\n\n    Args:\n    - grid (np.ndarray): The input grid.\n    - i (int): The row index of the point.\n    - j (int): The column index of the point.\n\n    Returns:\n    - bool: True if there are red points in the left and right directions of the given point, False otherwise.\n    \"\"\"\n    left = False\n    right = False\n    for k in range(j):\n        if grid[i][k] == red:\n            left = True\n            break\n    for k in range(j + 1, grid.shape[1]):\n        if grid[i][k] == red:\n            right = True\n            break\n    return left and right\ndef color_to_maroon(grid: np.ndarray, i: int, j: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Colors the given point in the grid to maroon.\n\n    Args:\n    - grid (np.ndarray): The input grid.\n    - i (int): The row index of the point.\n    - j (int): The column index of the point.\n\n    Returns:\n    - np.ndarray: The updated grid with the given point colored to maroon.\n    \"\"\"\n    grid[i][j] = maroon\n    return grid", "holes": {"has_red_neighbors_in_horizontal_directions": "you get a grid and a point. you should check if there are red point in left direction and right direction at the same time. These red points do not necessarily need to be adjacent, just need be on the same row. Checks if there are red points in the left and right directions of the given point.", "color_to_maroon": "color this point to maroon"}}
